dox shows in this study, it can also introduce new class and race tensions, and even exacerbate inequalities. Sensitively navigating the pros and cons of middle-class transformation, When Middle-Class Parents Choose Urban Schools asks whether it is possible for our urban public schools to have both financial security and equitable diversity. Drawing on in-depth research at an urban elementary school, Posey-Maddox examines parents’ efforts to support the school through their outreach, marketing, and volunteerism. She shows that when middle-class parents engage in urban school communities, they can bring a host of positive benefits, including new educational opportunities and greater diversity. But their involvement can also unintentionally marginalize less-affluent parents and diminish low-income students’ access to the improving schools. In response, Posey-Maddox argues that school reform efforts, which usually equate improvement with rising test scores and increased enrollment, need to have more equity-focused policies in place to ensure that low-income families also benefit from—and participate in—school change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunity and schoolzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in educationzUnited States. 0aEducationxParent participationzUnited States. 0aMiddle classxEducationzUnited States. 0aPublic schoolszUnited States. 0aSchool management and organizationxParent participationzUnited States. 0aSegregation in educationzUnited States. 0aUrban schoolsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022612018840uhttps://www.d